      "title": "Population genetics of parasitic protozoa and other microorganisms",
      "abstract": "Publisher Summary This chapter deals with population genetics of microorganisms, focusing on medically important parasitic protozoa and fungal organisms. It presents comparisons of parasitic protozoa and fungal organisms with population genetics of bacteria. The need to analyze a data in population genetic is crucial and increases proportionally with the scale of time and space considered. The risk that gene exchange interferes with genotype stability is especially great in the genera having a well-known sexual cycle. The risk of sex interfering with the stability of the genotype cannot be ruled out for any microbe, without careful population genetic analysis. Time scale is a central problem in selecting the appropriate marker with a level of resolution. Progress in theoretical interpretation of genetic data depends upon the possibilities of building bridges between previously separate lines of research studying different kinds of microbe. The development of the comparative population genetics makes it possible: (1) to strain typing so that it becomes a really routine and reliable epidemiological tool, (2) to improve and codify microbial taxonomy, and (3) to address the linked central questions which are unanswered."
